Chinese New Year officially starts on January 22, 2023 and the Year of the Rabbit will be celebrated. According to the Chinese zodiac, 2023 is predicted to be “the year of hope”, it is also extremely lucky for those born in the years of Rabbit, Goat, Pig and Rat. Here’s what the four animal signs can expect from the next 13 months. The Chinese zodiac is represented by 12 animals. In order, they are the Rat, Ox, Tiger, Rabbit, Dragon, Snake, Horse, Goat, Monkey, Rooster, Dog, and Pig. Each year is represented by a zodiac animal, and there is a 12-year cycle. Chinese people believe a person's horoscope, personality, and love compatibility are closely associated with his/her Chinese zodiac sign, which is determined by his/her birth year. READ MORE: What the Year of the Rabbit has in store for all 12 animal signs Born in the years: 1951, 1963, 1975, 1987, 1999, 2011, 2023 It “goes without saying”, this year will be a “prosperous period” where Rabbits will be “regarded for past generous deeds”. “Unprecedented opportunities” will be offered “on a plate” and this could be in the form of a promotion at work, or a substantial salary increase. In love, single Rabbits can meet their “soulmate”, astrologists suggest. DON'T MISS...Subtle design changes Kate Middleton makes to modernise old outfits [STYLE]Grab a McDonald’s Big Mac or Quarter Pounder for just £1.49 [OFFERS]Martin Lewis’ two ‘simple rules’ to burn 4,000 calories a day [COMMENT] Born in the years: 1943, 1955, 1967, 1979, 1991, 2003, 2015 2027, 2015 “Long-awaited success is just around the corner” for Goat in terms of career and money, it could be a promotion or significant career advancement. When it comes to finances, astrologers say money “has the potential to trick down like endless warm rain” this year, and gains will “satisfy [your] wildest hopes”. According to the 2023 love horoscope, the Chinese New Year is all about “re-shaping feelings”. READ MORE: Luckiest animals in the Year of the Rabbit 2023 Goat Born i